article.description: Adonal Foyle collected 16 points, a career-high 20 rebounds and four blocks as the Warriors ended a three-game slide with a 113-98 victory over the Phoenix Suns.
article.headline: Warriors 2½ games out of playoff spot
article.linkText: Warriors rip Suns, close playoff gap to 2½ games
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) _ The Golden State Warriors won't quite let themselves say it just yet. But it's on everyone's mind.
Jamison

The playoffs? "Yes!'' said coach Eric Musselman's 7-year-old son, Michael, on whether it would be a big lift for this franchise. Antawn Jamison had 23 points and 11 rebounds and the Warriors kept themselves in the postseason hunt, defeating the Phoenix Suns 113-98 Tuesday night to snap a three-game losing streak. Golden State picked up a half-game on idle Houston and moved within 2½ games of Phoenix for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Western Conference. Even to be in the mix for a possible postseason berth is amazing for this team, which hasn't been to the playoffs in nine years. That's probably why the Warriors have such a hard time talking about it. Musselman passed the microphone to his son when asked about the subject. "We talk about it a little bit as a group,'' Musselman finally acknowledged, in a hushed voice. "This was a monumental win for us, it really was.'' The Warriors' 31 victories are the most for the organization since going 30-52 in 1996-97. Gilbert Arenas added 22 points and five assists, Adonal Foyle had 16 points and a career-high 20 rebounds and Jason Richardson and Troy Murphy scored 13 points each for the Warriors. Murphy also had 12 rebounds. Amare Stoudemire led the Suns with 24 points and eight rebounds, but they couldn't overcome Golden State's shooting or their own sluggishness. Phoenix was flat in every facet of the game and got outhustled, especially on the boards, where the Suns were outrebounded 58-41. "We got beat on the boards, we got beat on the fast break,'' Stoudemire said. "It was a tough loss.'' Earl Boykins scored five points as the Warriors opened the fourth quarter with a 9-0 spurt to build a 93-73 lead. Boykins scored 10 in the final period, the ninth time he's had 10 or more in the fourth. Phoenix lost for the ninth time in 13 games. Five of the losses were by a combined 10 points. The Warriors know how it feels -- they lost some close ones last weekend. Golden State went on the road carrying a season-best six-game winning streak, but lost at Chicago, Milwaukee and Detroit. The Bucks beat them by five in overtime after the Warriors blew a 16-point lead, and the Pistons won by two on a buzzer-beater. "I unequivocally thought that this team would play as hard as it played all year tonight after the way they played in Detroit,'' Musselman said. "There's no quit in this team whatsoever. There's a lot of belief in one another. It was a confident ballclub after going 0-3 on the road trip.'' Golden State reached .500 last week for the first time since 1994. Foyle, who platoons with starter Erick Dampier, also wouldn't say much about the playoff push. "I think it's dirty because there's not an easy road or path to that end,'' he said. "We have a lot of work to do.'' The Suns couldn't believe they'd allowed the 6-foot-10 backup center to grab 20 boards. Foyle also had four blocks, two steals and three assists. Stoudemire dunked with 2:06 left in the second quarter to pull the Suns within 55-50, but the Warriors outscored the Suns 9-2 the rest of the way for a 64-52 halftime lead. The game was never close again. "We were in the game, but in the last two minutes of the second quarter they made a run and started the third the same way,'' Stoudemire said. As it has been lately, the arena was rocking as the first half ended. Fans were on their feet to show their appreciation for a team that made one of the most impressive turnarounds in the league. Golden State made seven of its first eight shots to build a 14-6 lead, while Phoenix was 3-for-10 to start the game. The Warriors had lost 24 of 29 to the Suns, including 9 of 12 at home.

Game notes
The Suns dropped to 11-21 on the road, including 5-14 against the West. ... Warriors F Chris Mills missed the game with tendinitis in his left Achilles' tendon. His status is day-to-day. ... Golden State F Danny Fortson rejoined the team after sitting out four games because of the death of a family member. ... Musselman's reaction about his alma mater San Diego winning the West Coast Conference tournament and earning an automatic NCAA bid: "I'm really jacked up,'' he said. The last time the Toreros won the conference tournament was Musselman's senior season in 1987. They also made it the former guard's freshman season in 1983.
